07187nam a22010575i 9783110198904DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20082007gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013941044  a97831101989047 a10.1515/97831101989042doi  a(DE-B1597)34620  a(OCoLC)853249485  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a410.1  aES 4802rvk0(DE-625)rvk/27847:00aNew Challenges in Typology :bBroadening the Horizons and Redefining the Foundations /ced. by Matti Miestamo, Bernhard Wälchli. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (407 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v1890 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe sixteen chapters in this volume are written by typologists and typologically oriented field linguists who have completed their Ph.D. theses in the first four years of this millennium. The authors address selected theoretical questions of general linguistic relevance drawing from a wealth of data hitherto unfamiliar to the general linguistic audience. The general aim is to broaden the horizons of typology by revisiting existing typologies with larger language samples, exploring domains not considered in typology before, taking linguistic diversity more seriously, strengthening the connection between typology and areal linguistics, and bridging the gap to other fields, such as historical linguistics and sociolinguistics. The papers cover grammatical phenomena from phonology, morphology up to the syntax of complex sentences. The linguistic phenomena scrutinized include the following: foot and stress, tone, infixation, inflection vs. derivation, word formation, polysynthesis, suppletion, person marking, reflexives, alignment, transitivity, tense-aspect-mood systems, negation, interrogation, converb systems, and complex sentences. More general methodological and theoretical issues, such as reconstruction, markedness, semantic maps, templates, and use of parallel corpora, are also addressed. The contributions in this volume draw from many traditional fields of linguistics simultaneously, and show that it is becoming harder and maybe also less desirable to keep them separate, especially when taking a broadly cross-linguistic approach to language. The book is of interest to typologists and field linguists, as well as to any linguists interested in theoretical issues in different subfields of linguistics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aTypology (Linguistics). 4aTypologie (Sprache). 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aLinguistic Typology.  aendangered languages.1 aAldai, Gontzal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoupe, A. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCysouw, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález, Carolina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGood, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHildebrandt, Kristine A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiestamo, Matti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiestamo, Matti, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNæss, Åshild, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPuddu, Nicoletta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSakel, Jeanette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaulwick, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerstraete,